Causes of renal papillary necrosis (RPN)

Source

[!TIP] Mnemonic : POSTCARDS

  1. Pyelonephritis
  2. Obstruction
  3. Sickle cell disease
  4. Tuberculosis
  5. Cirrhosis, chronic alcoholism
  6. Analgesic abuse
  7. Renal transplant rejection
  8. Diabetes mellitus
  9. Systemic vasculitis
  • Renal papillary necrosis is coagulative necrosis of the renal papilla (the apex of the renal pyramid) secondary to ischemia.
  • It may occur as a complication of severe pyelonephritis but it does not always follow infection.
  • papillary necrosis can predispose to infection of the necrotic site or act as a focus for calculus formation.
  • The papillae have a poor blood supply despite being supplied by the vasa recta (arising from the efferent arterioles) and the interlobar branches of the renal artery.
  • RPN is easily induced experimentally by administering a combination of aspirin (inhibits PGE) and phenacetin (highyy nephrotoxic)

#2015MCQ-APR/Q04

Enveloped, single stranted RNA virus.
It can survive for several hours on fomites. (upto 48) Source

Symptoms:

  • Uncomplicated disease
    • Fever, corrhyzal symptoms
    • Constitutional symptoms
    • Red and watery eyes
    • Non productive Cough
    • Sore throat
  • Older adults and immunosuppresed patients may have fewer symptoms but confusion is commoner among older patients.
  • Physical examination of the lungs is normal

Complicated disease

  • Pneumonia - usually occurs within a few days of onset: cough becomes purulent and productive. Commonest cause is Strep. pneumoniae. Source
  • Myocarditis, pericarditis, myocardial infarction, CNS involvement, myositis, rhabdomyolysis can all occur.
  • CNS: Seizures, encephalitis, Guillain barre syndrome,
    • It can also cause a parkinson like syndrome called "encephalitis lethargica" Source

Why is vaccination so common?

Transmission - very high risk because:

  • Incubation period - 2 days; but transmission can occur before symptoms onset and even from asymptomatic persons.
    Diagnosis:
  • Usually clinical but if necessary, viral culture from nasopharyngeal swabs is the gold standard. Antigen kits are specific but not very sensitive.
  • Mainstay is prevention with the vaccine; new vaccines are now quadrivalent. (2 A subtypes and 2 B subtypes)
  • Vaccination is recommended for any trimester of pregnancy. It also confirs protection to the newborn.
    • Oseltamivir reduces duration of symptoms and duration of viral shedding.
    • Treatment duration is 5 days.
  • Vaccines are the best method of prevention. However, if vaccine is contraindicated or ineffective (patient is immunosuppresed), antivirals (oseltamivir) can be used for prophylaxis.
  • Other drugs include Amantadine (yes.. antiparkinsons drug) and rimantadine which blocks the viral M2 proton channel but there is not high resistance to these drugs (in the USA) so not recommended for use there.

Antigenic drift and antigenic shift

  • Influenza is an RNA virus so there is no proof reading mechanism during RNA synthesis. Therefore, mutation accumulate over time. This is called antigenic drift.
  • Antigenic shift refers to drastic changes in genome. This happens when influenza A and infleunza B simultaneously infect a cell and their genomes mix to form a new virus.
  • This can happen because the infleunza genome is segmented into eight piecies which can be reshuffled during coinfection of a cell.
    • eg H1N1 and H5N2 strains can coinfect a cells and produce H5N1.
    • Antigenic shift causes pandemics.
  • Influenza B can only undergo antigenic drift.
  • Influenza A is capable for undergoing antigenic shift.

Compounds with high hepatic extraction show clearance rates that are directly dependent on hepatic blood flow. If fewer compounds are delivered to the liver, fewer compounds are removed from the circulation. In contrast, generally, compounds with lower extraction ratios tend to be blood flow independent Source
